user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following metal_softirq_set_enable code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 17.8.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 17.8 is A function parameter should not be modified.
Note that the object referred to by a pointer parameter may be modified, but the pointer itself shall not be modified.
</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of metal_softirq_set_enable.
```c
static void metal_softirq_set_enable(struct metal_irq_controller *cntr,
				     int irq, unsigned int enable)
{
	if (irq < cntr->irq_base ||
	    irq >= (cntr->irq_base + cntr->irq_num)) {
		return;
	}

	irq -= cntr->irq_base;
	if (enable ==  METAL_IRQ_ENABLE) {
		atomic_store(&metal_softirq_enabled[irq], 1);
	} else {
		atomic_store(&metal_softirq_enabled[irq], 0);
	}
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The parameter 'irq' (an int passed by value) is modified by the statement 'irq -= cntr->irq_base;'. Rule 17.8 prohibits modifying function parameters, so this is a violation. (The pointer parameter 'cntr' is only dereferenced, which is permitted.)
</scenario>

